<HEADLINE>
<P>
MOUNTAIN LION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The recent killing of the woman by the mountain lion in Northern California is 
no less tragic knowing it is the first such attack this century. We are all 
aware of the risks we may encounter when visiting wilderness areas.However, the 
swift decision by the Department of Fish and Game "bounty hunters" to enforce 
the death penalty against this cat and its subsequent shooting (May 2) only 
reinforces my opinion of this department's frequent "kill it" solution to any 
wildlife resource issue that presents itself. 
</P>
<P>
 Too bad that all the serial killers, rapists, and other human garbage sitting 
on death row at taxpayers' huge expense aren't dealt with in a similar manner. 
</P>
<P>
 STARLA IBBS 
</P>
<P>
 Whittier 
</P>
<P>
 Let me see if I understand the logic of the Department of Fish and Game. If we 
choose to live in or on a border of a wilderness area and a wild animal wanders 
into a neighborhood and attacks a human, the suspected animal is tracked down 
and killed. However, if a human deliberately goes into a wild habitat and is 
attacked, the suspected animal is tracked down and killed. Do I have that 
right? 
</P>
<P>
 Sounds like a "lose-lose" situation for wildlife. 
</P>
<P>
 JAMES K. ANDERSON 
</P>
<P>
 Brentwood 
</P>
