<HEADLINE>
<P>
COLLEGES SCORE WINDFALL SELLING ADS ON ATHLETES; SPORTS: NIKE AND REEBOK DEALS 
BUOY CASH-STRAPPED PROGRAMS, CAMPUS OFFICIALS SAY. OTHERS SEE EXPLOITATION. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAN CRAY, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Hundreds of miniature billboards have begun springing up at UCLA, and they're 
an advertiser's dream. They're flashy, appealing to young people and, in a good 
year, could even draw national attention. 
</P>
<P>
 The billboards also happen to be student athletes. 
</P>
<P>
 In a move that is becoming more common at major universities, UCLA in February 
signed a six-year, $4.35-million agreement with Reebok under which the shoe 
manufacturer will supply the uniforms, warm-up gear and shoes for every 
athletic team on campus. Reebok gets to put its logo on all the sports clothing 
-- everything from batting gloves to jackets to the school's football uniforms 
will now bear Reebok's "vector" icon. 
</P>
<P>
 The agreement comes less than a year after USC signed a similar contract with 
Nike. 
</P>
<P>
 The two Southern California schools are among the first in the country to sign 
such contracts. Although school officials say this will provide badly needed 
revenue, some people contend that it is merely another way in which student 
athletes are used. 
</P>
<P>
 "In this day and age, all college athletic departments are up against 
financial hardships, and this is one way we can create a stream of revenue," 
said Mark Brantley, director of corporate relations at USC. "There is that 
other side of the coin where people say, 'Hey, you're putting stuff on the 
athletes and making money off of it,' but they're getting an education here and 
it's all part of the process of us running a business. That's the way we look 
at it. It's a business, and we're generating revenue." 
</P>
<P>
 USC, citing its status as a private university, has refused to divulge how 
much money it received, but sources say the school probably received several 
million dollars. 
</P>
<P>
 In exchange for supplying school teams with uniforms, Nike will be allowed to 
advertise on banners at volleyball and tennis tournaments, on the video board 
at the Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum and on the rotating board at the Sports 
Arena. 
</P>
<P>
 The deals are a combination of cash and athletic apparel. At UCLA, for 
instance, roughly half of the $4.35 million will be paid in cash, the rest in 
the value of the apparel. 
</P>
<P>
 After signing its contract with UCLA, Reebok reached a similar deal with the 
University of Texas and agreed to sponsor every athletic program at Georgia 
State University except basketball. Nike, meanwhile, has all-sports deals with 
the University of Miami and the University of North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
 Officials from USC and UCLA say the advertising is not intrusive and offers 
much-needed revenue for their athletic departments. Others, however, denounce 
the deals. 
</P>
<P>
 "The students are being asked to be walking advertisements," said Erwin 
Chemerinsky, professor of law at USC. "This only happens because in the college 
sports arena, we accept it. If Coca-Cola were to go to another department and 
offer to donate money in exchange for every member of that department's faculty 
wearing a bright red blazer with the Coca-Cola logo on it when they went to 
class, no one would have any doubt it would violate the 1st Amendment. I know I 
wouldn't wear it." 
</P>
<P>
 In fact, both Coca-Cola and Pepsi have had sponsorship arrangements with 
several universities for about three years, but those deals pertain only to the 
soft drinks sold on campus and do not call for students to wear advertising. 
Such deals, at schools including Penn State, Texas A & M and Cal State 
Sacramento, pertain to all vending machines and beverages sold on campus. No 
Southern California schools have such agreements. 
</P>
<P>
 Until now, the practice has been for shoe companies to pay stipends to coaches 
for use in selected athletic programs -- mostly football and basketball. In 
exchange, the coach would have players wear a particular brand of shoes. Now, 
all-inclusive sponsorship arrangements are being reached more often. Although 
some of the nation's better-known coaches will retain their contracts -- USC's 
George Raveling, for example -- shoe manufacturers say they are hoping to steer 
clear of such deals in the future. 
</P>
<P>
 "The trend is to move toward schoolwide deals," said Keith Peters, a spokesman 
for Nike. "Certain schools have good sports reputations, and with those schools 
we'd rather have the whole program." 
</P>
<P>
 Financially strapped athletic departments are usually more than happy to enter 
such deals. 
</P>
<P>
 Earlier this year, UCLA announced plans to discontinue its men's swimming and 
men's and women's gymnastics programs for lack of funding. 
</P>
<P>
 Women's gymnastics was later reinstated and the fate of the other two will be 
determined at a court hearing, but campus officials say that if not for the 
deal with Reebok, other programs would have come under scrutiny as well. 
</P>
<P>
 Cash-strapped students say they also benefit from the deals. 
</P>
<P>
 For Allison West, a sophomore on the UCLA women's soccer team, the Reebok deal 
meant saving the $200 she says it cost her to pay for athletic gear last 
season. 
</P>
<P>
 "Women's soccer was a club sport last year, meaning there were no corporate 
sponsors and you had to buy everything on your own," she said. "This year, I 
have four pairs of shoes, five jackets, everything." 
</P>
<P>
 That is just one reason school officials say student athletes aren't being 
exploited. 
</P>
<P>
 "I would object to any suggestion we are selling out the students," said Glenn 
Toth, UCLA's associate athletic director for corporate sales and sponsorships, 
who negotiated the deal with Reebok. "The fact of life, at least as far as 
college athletics is concerned, is that two sports are revenue-producing sports 
and 18 sports are not. If you are to have a broad-based athletic program like 
we like to have, it makes sense to offset as many hard-dollar expenses as you 
can in order to maintain that type of diversity." 
</P>
<P>
 But in making such arguments, colleges are trying to have it both ways, says 
Sonny Vaccaro, the former Nike marketing expert credited with pioneering shoe 
company deals with college coaches in 1978. Although all-sports sponsorship 
deals are a new twist, Vaccaro says, it doesn't change the fact that the 
students receive no compensation for their role. 
</P>
<P>
 "(Universities) are renting space on the student athlete's body, and he's not 
getting anything for it," said Vaccaro, who lives in Los Angeles and now works 
for Adidas. "I think there will be a time and place where some college athlete 
is going to change that." 
</P>
<P>
 Vaccaro's opinion reflects a desire shared by most marketing experts in the 
shoe industry: to ease NCAA rules that prevent athletes from accepting monetary 
compensation. That would almost certainly eliminate any need for shoe 
manufacturers to reach deals with coaches or universities; instead, they could 
select key athletes and negotiate on an individual basis, as they do with 
professional athletes. 
</P>
<P>
 But whatever Vaccaro's motivations, other experts agree that athletes are 
being used. At both UCLA and USC, for example, athletes must wear the 
logo-laden team apparel or risk not participating in sports. Even "spatting" -- 
covering corporate logos with tape -- will be permitted only in rare instances. 
</P>
<P>
 "If a student is unhappy because of the fit, or maybe because he's played in 
another brand all his life and he's superstitious, in that instance . . . the 
logo would probably be taped over," said UCLA's Toth. "There's very limited 
flexibility, but there is flexibility." 
</P>
<P>
 Legal scholars say public universities, which receive government funds, stand 
the greatest chance of being tested on such policies in court, since 1st 
Amendment rights apply only to government businesses and agencies. But that 
doesn't mean private universities are free of risk. 
</P>
<P>
 "The catch on that is, universities like USC say they are going to follow the 
1st Amendment even if they don't have to," Chemerinsky notes. 
</P>
<P>
 As yet, no such case has emerged, in part because the new, multisport 
sponsorship agreements are just now coming into use and have not been widely 
publicized. The deals, however, are drawing some criticism on college campuses 
nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
 "All of this changes the relationship between a university and its athletes, 
now that the athletes are explicitly being made billboards for a commercial 
company," said John Weistart, a law professor at Duke University and outspoken 
critic of corporate sponsorships in collegiate athletics. "It's becoming harder 
and harder to talk about the athletes as students, because it looks like 
they're really just engaged in a money-making enterprise for the university." 
</P>
<P>
 Weistart questions how universities can agree to such big-money sponsorships 
and continue to retain tax-exempt status from the government, which excuses 
educational institutions from revenue taxes since they are engaged in public 
education. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think there's a very serious question as to why the money the university 
receives is not taxed," Weistart said. "If we had a professional team that 
entered into an equipment agreement, clearly the money they receive is taxable, 
so why shouldn't the money be taxable when it's received by a university? With 
their special status come some obligations, and one of those is that they must 
remain true to their educational purpose. It would be very unfair if 
universities, on the one hand, act in a highly commercialized fashion and then, 
on the other hand, claim the special status of a nonprofit organization engaged 
in education." 
</P>
<P>
 Amid all the debate, no one disputes that student athletes have been left 
without a say. 
</P>
<P>
 Asked whether student athletes are, in effect, serving as billboards, Nike 
spokesman Peters said, "I'm not sure I can disagree with it. The fact is, that 
is the system in what is called collegiate amateur sports today. . . . To a 
certain extent, the schools are generating revenue both on the student 
athlete's performance and the team's performance." 
</P>
<P>
 Paul Hoffman, a Santa Monica-based civil rights attorney, said a precedent for 
such deals already exists in practically every community. "When you think about 
it, this is not so unusual," he said. "Little League is the same thing, but on 
a smaller scale. They need the sponsorships to keep the league running, and 
everyone expects it and no one is offended by it." 
</P>
<P>
 Many UCLA students agree, though in some cases reluctantly. 
</P>
<P>
 "It would be better if we could do it another way, but I don't think that's 
possible," said Michelle Regul, a member of the school's spirit squad, which 
also is covered by the deal. "They're going to get the shoes from one of the 
big shoe companies anyway. It doesn't matter to me if it's Reebok." 
</P>
<P>
 Tommy Bennett, a junior majoring in political science and a member of the 
school's football team, says he has no real qualms about the UCLA-Reebok deal. 
"The stuff is cool, and a lot of it's free, so it doesn't bother us at all," he 
said. "I'm comfortable with it. We're billboards, but we have nice shoes." 
</P>
</TEXT>
